{
  "_comment": "Millipede. examples/drawings/millipede.jpg is IMG_7699 rotated 103.1 deg (measured by PCA of the pen ink, not guessed) so the body lies horizontal with the legs pointing down and the head at the right; faces:'right' makes it travel the way it looks. Rotation only, never mirrored \u2014 we don't flip a child's drawing. The body is 9 chained segments, head-first, each pivoting at its parent-side edge on the body midline. Per-segment gait phase increases down the chain, so one sine travels head to tail; swing grows toward the tail so the head steers and the tail whips. This is the first rig that needs REAL hierarchical transforms: with the old flat transforms each segment would rotate about a fixed pivot independently and shear the body apart instead of bending it. Legs are the hatch marks along the bottom edge and ride their segment \u2014 rigging ~60 individual legs would be absurd and invisible at this scale.",
